column9: Lifetime: The number of people who had your Page's post enter their screen. Posts include statuses, photos, links, videos and more. (Unique Users)

column3:
#ArtAIDSChi will feature a number of Open TV artists when it commences programming next month! Work by Karen Finley, who will be guest starring in Brujos next year, has been touring with exhibit.

In response to the HIV epidemic of the 1980s, artists began creating politically outspoken pieces to explore and expose the crisis that changed the world forever. Art AIDS America Chicago is free to the public and opens World AIDS Day (December 1, 2016). Experience the exhibition by reserving your spot at http://ArtAIDSAmericaChicago.org

Brujos profiled in the Windy City Times as it's campaign gets closer to completion!

"It's really important to me that this is not just a gay show, or a Latino show, because gay people and Latino people don't occur in a vacuum, they live in an ecosystem of a world that's contoured by multiple identities. When entitled gay men write 'no Blacks, no Latinos, no Asians, no fats' on their Grindr profiles, we're responding with a show centered on those excluded people." -- Ricardo Gamboa

DONATE AND SHARE: http://indiegogo.com/projects/brujos-a-queer-of-color-webseries-magic

Thank you to Brianna Wellen of the Chicago Reader for profiling Open TV and our event at the Chicago Humanities Festival on Saturday! Join us Saturday at Northwestern's Block Museum of Art from 4-6PM where we'll be spotlighting Nic Kay, Ricardo Gamboa, and Shea Couleé!

Open TV artists are brilliant and brave. Rashida KhanBey, writer and star of #OpenTVPresents #LetGoandLetGod, just wrote this powerful statement on why she created the piece:

"It was in church that day that I wrote the outline for my second film 'Let Go & Let God.' I wanted to document a woman’s journey of battling the grief and depression after burying the pain for so long. We come in on the time period where everything explodes and she chooses to rise....I know there is a woman who feels that she is struggling in this experience alone. I wrote this piece and created this film to tell you that you are not alone."

Congratulations Andre Perez for winning one of the top awards from the Propeller Fund for "Living Trans History" where he and his collaborators will be screening the #OpenTVOriginals series #BeenThere!

Kiam Marcelo Junio, star of #NupitaObama who brought their yoga and performance practice to #OpenTVPresents, talks about both practices in this blog for Western Illinois University: "I have felt for so long that everything is performance and cause even at home, even by yourself, you’re still performing.  We’re still performing even these conscious things that we learn, that we are taught."

Congratulations Samantha Bailey (Brown Girls, You're So Talented), Scrappers Film Group (Brujos), and Andre Perez (#BeenThere) for this recognition from New City magazine! #OpenTVCommunity

"I really try to make the crew working behind the camera reflect the stories we’re telling in front of it. I’ve found a group of people, who happen to be women, people of color, queer, or a combination of these, who are hella talented and really believe in that sort of filmmaking, which has been very helpful." -- Sam Bailey, 

http://newcityfilm.com/2016/10/13/film-50-2016
